# Fluff Date: 2026-02-16 11:04:06
overview:<p>When General Aleksandr Kerensky laid down the design specifications for the Atlas, he said it should be "a 'Mech as powerful as imaginable, as impenetrable as possible, and as foreboding as conceivable, so that fear itself will be our ally." With the Regular army increasingly concerned with the growing strength of the House Lords' personal armies, a new and powerful 'Mech was needed. Despite the coming war and the abandonment of the Inner Sphere by General Kerensky and most of the SLDF, the Atlas served its purpose.</p>

capabilities:<p>The first impression any spectator gets of the Atlas is its ferocious appearance. The famous skull-head took designers a full year to perfect, and although there are taller 'Mechs on the field, none of them have the sheer presence of the Atlas.</p><p>As an assault 'Mech, the Atlas has few peers. The largest long-range missile launcher available sits in the left torso, giving the Atlas a powerful long-range punch. As the 'Mech closes it can bring a bevy of deadly weapons to bear, the most fearsome of which is the massive Defiance 'Mech Hunter Autocannon in the right torso with enough ammunition to decimate a company of 'Mechs. The cannon is backed by a six-tube short-range missile system and two pairs of medium lasers covering all sides of the 'Mech. Twenty heat sinks give the Atlas the freedom to use this firepower, and most MechWarriors are fearful of this 'Mech for very deserved reasons.</p><p>Very few if any BattleMechs carry more armor than the Atlas, and a complete set of actuators (including hands) give the 'Mech frightful physical combat capabilities. There are myths among MechWarriors of the Atlas actually picking up lighter 'Mechs and breaking them like toys.</p><p>If the Atlas has any weakness it would be its slow speed. Although other assault 'Mechs are as slow, the fact that an Atlas is easily escaped is the hope most MechWarriors have when they face such a machine.</p>

deployment:<p>A unique custom refit from the Outworlds Alliance, this Atlas was extensively modified with a hyper-velocity AC/10, snub-nose PPC, Thunderbolt 15 launcher, and light PPCs in the arms. CASE II protection safeguarded the ammunition bays while a cockpit command console, Beagle active probe, and remote sensor dispensers provided exceptional battlefield awareness. The eclectic weapons mix and extensive electronics suite suggested the 'Mech was designed for independent operations in the Periphery, where versatility and situational awareness were more valuable than raw firepower.</p>

history:<p>The Atlas was born of necessity. Between 2751 and 2761, the Cameron Edicts passed by the High Council permitted the five House Lords to double the size of their personal armies. The Regular Army needed a weapon that could maintain its supremacy over these swelling forces. General Aleksandr Kerensky himself laid down the specifications, demanding "a 'Mech as powerful as possible, as impenetrable as possible, and as ugly and foreboding as conceivable, so that fear itself will be our ally." Designers took this mandate to heart, spending an entire year perfecting the skull-shaped head that would earn the Atlas its enduring nickname: the "Death's Head."</p><p>The Atlas saw its baptism of fire against Stefan the Usurper during the liberation of Terra. In the final battles to secure Earth's major spaceports, the Atlas was instrumental in establishing beachheads that allowed SLDF troops to land safely. General Kerensky's second-in-command, General Aaron DeChavilier, spearheaded the assault on the Usurper's last stronghold, the Imperial City. DeChavilier continually exposed his Atlas to enemy fire, marching forward as if laser bolts, missiles, and cannon shells were nothing more than the annoying buzz of flies. When DeChavilier's Atlas pushed over the concrete outer wall surrounding the Imperial Palace, Kerensky headed for the gates in his Orion. It was a scene that would be immortalized in countless holovids and paintings, forever linking the Atlas to the liberation of humanity's homeworld.</p><p>When Kerensky departed on his Exodus, he wanted all Atlases to accompany him. More than two-thirds of Atlas pilots, however, refused to join, perhaps believing they could better their fortunes by remaining in the Inner Sphere. The remaining Atlases and those still rolling off assembly lines on Hesperus II, Al Na'ir, and Quentin continued to inspire terror wherever they walked. As the Succession Wars ravaged the Inner Sphere, the Atlas spread to every major military in limited numbers. Most militaries were loath to tamper with the design for the simple reason that it seemed nearly perfect in its role already, and attempted modifications generally failed since engineers had to make too many concessions to keep the 'Mech functioning.</p><p>The Atlas cemented its legend during some of the most pivotal moments in Inner Sphere history. On Mallory's World in 3013, First Prince Ian Davion of the Federated Suns held a vital pass against Yorinaga Kurita and the Second Sword of Light while his men made their escape. Although the Kell Hounds and other units pushed forward to support him, Prince Davion fell in battle before help could arrive. A warrior first and a leader second, his sacrifice from the cockpit of an Atlas became one of the most celebrated last stands in military history. Two decades later, the sight of Hanse Davion's Atlases and Victors standing in formation for honors after actions against House Kurita reminded the Inner Sphere that the 'Mech remained the gold standard of assault warfare.</p><p>The technological renaissance of the 3040s and 3050s breathed new life into the venerable design. The Draconis Combine debuted the AS7-K variant, transforming the Atlas from a short-ranged brawler into a long-range bombardier. The highly desired Gauss rifle replaced the super-heavy autocannon while arm-mounted ER large lasers extended the 'Mech's reach considerably. Despite being an ancient design, the Atlas' reputation on the battlefield remained unquestioned - even state-of-the-art machines gave it a wide berth. This was, after all, the flagship of all BattleMechs, and there was still no projected date for it to be replaced.</p><p>The Jihad tested the Atlas as never before. On Al Na'ir in early 3069, a lance of corporate-owned Atlases held off wave after wave of Word of Blake troops while defending a dome settlement for several days, eventually succumbing only to penetrating torso hits that depressurized and crippled their extra-light engines. The Word of Blake's capture of Hesperus II in 3070 temporarily halted Defiance Industries' production lines. This crisis, however, spurred the development of the AS7-K2 on Defiance's Furillo facilities. When Hesperus was finally liberated, the faster K2 variant - powered by a Vlar 400 XL engine that frequently caught opponents off guard - entered full production. By 3085, twenty percent of Atlas BattleMechs in Lyran service were of this new type.</p><p>Through all of this, the Atlas has transcended its role as a mere weapon of war to become a cultural icon. It appears on more recruiting posters, more propaganda films, and in the boxes of more children's toys than any other BattleMech. More than a dozen variants have appeared over the centuries, each one building on a legacy that stretches back to the final days of the Star League. Whether defending a beleaguered colony or leading an assault on a fortified position, the sight of the Death's Head advancing across the battlefield continues to inspire allies and strike fear into enemies, just as General Kerensky intended nearly three centuries ago.</p>

